3. Fractal Substrates and Recursive Learning

The universe exhibits self-similar patterns across scales:

S = \bigcup_{i=1}^{n} S_i, \quad I_{i+1} = f(I_i, S_i)

where each  S_i  is a subsystem (cell, ecosystem, planet), and  I_{i+1}  depends recursively on prior intelligence  I_i  at a smaller scale.

This formalism allows AGI to:

· Propagate knowledge across scales via hierarchical inference
· Bound errors within local fractal layers
· Maintain overall system stability

Recent empirical support: Martins (2025) demonstrates that fractal small-world architectures support critical dynamics and task-related spatial reconfiguration while preserving global topological parameters. The paper provides experimental tools to measure recursive hierarchical embedding in both biological and artificial systems. These results directly validate our claim that error-bounding is observable in well-designed hierarchical systems.

Error propagation control: In hierarchical active inference, higher levels observe lower-level belief updating and modulate precision (inverse variance) of prediction errors. This enables a form of meta-learning where errors are escalated only when they cannot be resolved locally – a natural mechanism for bounding mistakes within fractal layers.

