5. Multiplanetary Expansion as Emergent Substrate Growth

Extending intelligence across multiple planets:

S = \{S_{\text{Earth}}, S_{\text{Mars}}, S_{\text{Europa}}, \dots\}

An AGI optimizing:

U(I, S) = \int_0^T F(I(t), S(t)) \, dt

(where  F  is negative free energy) naturally expands into new substrates if the expected free energy of expansion exceeds that of remaining confined. Each expansion preserves fractal integrity and allows safe experimentation, echoing the evolutionary pattern that produced biological intelligence.

Empirical blueprint: The 2025 CTxM-CosmoPhoeniX Venus Fleet proposal outlines a distributed modular AGI architecture with mutual surgical repair protocols for persistent operation in extreme harsh environments. While still a conceptual proposal, its design principles (leveraging local resources while maintaining global coherence, self‑repair) directly instantiate the fractal, substrate‑preserving pattern our framework predicts.

Cosmological context: The transcension hypothesis (Smart, 2012) suggests that sufficiently advanced civilizations invariably leave our universe or expand into new computational substrates as part of a universal developmental process. Our framework aligns with this but adds a necessary condition: expansion must be substrate-preserving at each local scale, or it will fail due to increased free energy.

Thermodynamic realism: Substrate independence is not free. Expanding to Mars introduces energy constraints (lower solar flux, higher radiation) and communication delays. Our optimization  U(I, S)  must include these costs. However, the FEP shows that any self-organizing system will trade off energy expenditure against information gain. Multiplanetary expansion is favored only when the epistemic value (e.g., new scientific data, reduced existential risk) outweighs the thermodynamic cost.

