6. CA-HRM Integration

Using Convergent Adaptive Hierarchical Reasoning Machines (CA-HRM):

· Intelligence is modeled as hierarchical latent computation
· Substrates define constraints on computation (e.g., precision, bandwidth, energy)
· Convergence dynamics ensure that intelligence self-regulates exploration, maintaining stability

Formally, the convergence map is:

I^{(k+1)} = \mathcal{F}(I^{(k)}, S^{(k)}, \epsilon)

where  \epsilon  represents permissible perturbations (errors). The system converges to stable, yet open-ended intelligence, balancing exploration and substrate preservation.

Empirical validation: The Hierarchical Reasoning Model (HRM) (Wang et al., 2025; arXiv:2506.21734v3) achieves 40.3% accuracy on the ARC-AGI-1 benchmark using only ~27 million parameters and ~1000 training examples. Its recurrent architecture, with modules operating at different timescales, enables hierarchical reasoning in a single forward pass and outperforms larger chain-of-thought models on inductive tasks. Independently, the Tiny Recursive Model (TRM) (Jolicoeur-Martineau, 2025; arXiv:2510.04871, 1st-place ARC Prize 2025 Paper Award) reaches ~44.6–45% on ARC-AGI-1 with only ~7M parameters via latent-state recursion and supervised refinement. The fact that two different architectures converged on recursive hierarchical decomposition provides strong convergent evidence that such structures are both necessary and efficient for general reasoning – a direct proof-of-concept for our  \mathcal{F}  map.

Relation to active inference: In hierarchical active inference,  I^{(k+1)}  is the updated posterior over hidden states after observing outcomes. The mapping  \mathcal{F}  corresponds to the Bayesian belief update:

I^{(k+1)} = \arg\min_{I} D_{KL}[Q(I) \| P(I | S, \epsilon)]

where  Q  is the approximate posterior and  P  is the generative model. Convergence is guaranteed under standard variational inference assumptions.

